{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Toxins of the scorpion calcine family bind directly to ryanodine receptors (RyRs), intracellular channel targets of the endoplasmic reticulum, and induce long lasting channel openings in a mode of smaller conductance. They have the ability to translocate into cells by crossing the plasma membrane [[cite:PUB00033810], [cite:PUB00033811], [cite:PUB00033812]].</p>\n<p>Toxins of scorpion calcine family are highly basic 33-amino acid peptides that present three disulphide bridges (C1-C4, C2-C5, and C3-C6) and fold along a knottin or inhibitor cystine knot motif  (https://www.dsimb.inserm.fr/KNOTTIN/)  [[cite:PUB00033810], [cite:PUB00033811], [cite:PUB00033812]]. Their three dimensional structure consists of a compact disulphide-bonded core from which emerge loops and the N terminus. The main element of regular secondary structure is a double-stranded antiparallel β-sheet. A third peripheral extended strand is almost perpendicular to the double-stranded antiparallel β-sheet [[cite:PUB00033811], [cite:PUB00016414]]. Scorpion calcine mimic the activating segment of the dihydropyridine receptor II-III loop, which interacts with a region of the ryanodine receptor  [[cite:PUB00033810], [cite:PUB00033811], [cite:PUB00033813]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"prosite" {"PS60028" "Scorpion calcine family signature"}, "pfam" {"PF08099" "Scorpion calcine family"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Scorpion calcine", "short" "Scorpion_calcine"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 5, "domain_architectures" 1, "proteomes" 29, "taxa" 333, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 110, "sets" 0, "proteins" 110, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 63}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"prositedoc" {"displayName" "PROSITE Doc", "description" "PROSITE is a database